frameDefinitions: A Perpetrator (generally intentionally) commits a Crime, i.e. does something not permitted by the laws of society.
This is an abstract frame for acts performed by sentient beings.
A Wrongdoer engages in a Misdeed.
This scenario describes a series of Events, associated with a single Participant, i.e., the history of the Participant.
An Agent causes a Patient to be affected, sometimes by a particular Means or by use of an Instrument.
frameExamples: They <t>perpetrated</t> a felony by substituting a lie for negotiations.
You have <t>sinned</t> for the last time, Stephen!
We've been worried about our recent hire's <t><fex name='Events'>history</fex></t> of deceiving employers.
A professional dishwasher doesn't <t>do</t> dishes with a rag anymore!
listRoleDefinitions: The individual that commits a <fen>Crime</fen>.
An act, generally intentional, that has been formally forbidden by law.
When the <fen>Crime</fen> was committed.
The location where the <fen>Crime</fen> occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Act</fen> that the <fen>Agent</fen> performs intentionally.
The <fen>Agent</fen> performs the intentional act.
This role identifies the time when the Agent acts intentionally.
This role identifies the place where the intentional act occurs.
This is the person whose <fen>Misdeed</fen> is being judged with respect to its morality.
The assessment of the <fen>Wrongdoer</fen> is based on his or her <fen>Misdeed</fen>.
The time at which a <fen>Misdeed</fen> is performed.
The location where a <fen>Misdeed</fen> occurs.

The <fen>Participant</fen> is either an active participant in all of the <fen>Events</fen> (e.g., Agent or Patient), or is more peripherally associated with the <fen>Events</fen> (e.g., Location or Topic).
The <fen>Events</fen> which the <fen>Participant</fen> is a part of. This role is used to mark the frame-evoking element.
When the <fen>Events</fen> concerning the <fen>Participant</fen> occured.
This role identifies the act that the <fen>Agent</fen> performs intentionally.
The conscious entity, generally a person, that performs the intentional act that affects the <fen>Patient</fen>.
Patient is the entity acted on and that may, but need not, undergo a change.
This role identifies the time when the <fen>Agent</fen> intentionally affects the <fen>Patient</fen>.
This role identifies the place where the <fen>Agent</fen> performs the intentional act.
listRoleExamples: How can <fex>he</fex> commit treason against the King of England in a foreign country , if he is not English?
How can he commit <fex>treason</fex> against the King of England in a foreign country , if he is not English?
A murder perpetrated <fex>at 1:08AM this morning</fex> was not investigated until noon today.
We have jurisdiction over crimes committed <fex>in Woodside County</fex>.
The misdeeds <fex>of the previous evening</fex> were all forgotten now.
Sexual peccadilloes <fex>in the White House</fex> are one thing, lying before Congress quite another.
We've been worried about <fex>our recent hire's</fex> history of deceiving employers.
We will focus on events in her recent <fex>history</fex>.
A professional dishwasher does <fex>dishes</fex> one at a time.
